<doc id="382694" wikidata="Q5161000" url="?curid=382694" title="Congruence subgroup">
<text>In mathematics, a congruence subgroup of a matrix group with integer entries is a subgroup defined by congruence conditions on the entries. A very simple example is the subgroup of invertible integer matrices of determinant 1 in which the off-diagonal entries are even. More generally, the notion of congruence subgroup can be defined for arithmetic subgroups of algebraic groups; that is, those for which we have a notion of &#x27;integral structure&#x27; and can define reduction maps modulo an integer.

The existence of congruence subgroups in an arithmetic group provides it with a wealth of subgroups, in particular it shows that the group is residually finite. An important question regarding the algebraic structure of arithmetic groups is the congruence subgroup problem, which asks whether all subgroups of finite index are essentially congruence subgroups.

Congruence subgroups of matrices are fundamental objects in the classical theory of modular forms; the modern theory of automorphic forms makes a similar use of congruence subgroups in more general arithmetic groups.

== Congruence subgroups of the modular group ==

The simplest interesting setting in which congruence subgroups can be studied is that of the modular group .

=== Principal congruence subgroups ===

If formula_1 is an integer there is a homomorphism formula_2 induced by the reduction modulo formula_3 morphism . The &quot;principal congruence subgroup of level formula_3&quot; in formula_5 is the kernel of , and it is usually denoted . Explicitly it is described as follows:
: formula_6

This definition immediately implies that formula_7 is a normal subgroup of finite index in . The strong approximation theorem (in this case an easy consequence of the Chinese remainder theorem) implies that formula_8 is surjective, so that the quotient formula_9 is isomorphic to . Computing the order of this finite group yields the following formula for the index:
: formula_10
where the product is taken over all prime numbers dividing .

If formula_11 then the restriction of formula_8 to any finite subgroup of formula_13 is injective. This implies the following result: 
: &quot;If formula_14 then the principal congruence subgroups formula_7 are torsion-free.&quot;
The group formula_16 contains formula_17 and is not torsion-free. On the other hand, its image in formula_18 is torsion-free, and the quotient of the hyperbolic plane by this subgroup is a sphere with three cusps.

=== Definition of a congruence subgroup ===

A subgroup formula_19 in formula_5 is called a &quot;congruence subgroup&quot; if there exists formula_1 such that formula_19 contains the principal congruence subgroup . The &quot;level&quot; formula_23 of formula_19 is then the smallest such .

From this definition it follows that:
* Congruence subgroups are of finite index in ; 
* The congruence subgroups of level formula_25 are in one-to-one correspondence with the subgroups of .

