<doc id="382708" wikidata="Q3491998" url="?curid=382708" title="Cofiniteness">
<text>In mathematics, a cofinite subset of a set formula_1 is a subset formula_2 whose complement in formula_1 is a finite set. In other words, formula_2 contains all but finitely many elements of formula_5 If the complement is not finite, but is countable, then one says the set is cocountable.

These arise naturally when generalizing structures on finite sets to infinite sets, particularly on infinite products, as in the product topology or direct sum. 

This use of the prefix &quot;&#x27;&quot; to describe a property possessed by a set&#x27;s &#x27;mplement is consistent with its use in other terms such as &quot;[[Cofiniteness|]]meagre set&quot;. 

==Boolean algebras==

The set of all subsets of formula_1 that are either finite or cofinite forms a Boolean algebra, which means that it is closed under the operations of union, intersection, and complementation. This Boolean algebra is the on formula_5

In the other direction, a Boolean algebra formula_2 has a unique non-principal ultrafilter (that is, a maximal filter not generated by a single element of the algebra) if and only if there exists an infinite set formula_1 such that formula_2 is isomorphic to the finite–cofinite algebra on formula_5 In this case, the non-principal ultrafilter is the set of all cofinite subsets of formula_1.

==Cofinite topology==

The cofinite topology or the finite complement topology is a topology that can be defined on every set formula_5 It has precisely the empty set and all cofinite subsets of formula_1 as open sets. As a consequence, in the cofinite topology, the only closed subsets are finite sets, or the whole of formula_5 For this reason, the cofinite topology is also known as the finite-closed topology. Symbolically, one writes the topology as
formula_16

This topology occurs naturally in the context of the Zariski topology. Since polynomials in one variable over a field formula_17 are zero on finite sets, or the whole of formula_18 the Zariski topology on formula_17 (considered as &quot;affine line&quot;) is the cofinite topology. The same is true for any &quot;irreducible&quot; algebraic curve; it is not true, for example, for formula_20 in the plane.

===Properties===

* Subspaces: Every subspace topology of the cofinite topology is also a cofinite topology.
* Compactness: Since every open set contains all but finitely many points of formula_21 the space formula_1 is compact and sequentially compact.
* Separation: The cofinite topology is the coarsest topology satisfying the T1 axiom; that is, it is the smallest topology for which every singleton set is closed. In fact, an arbitrary topology on formula_1 satisfies the T1 axiom if and only if it contains the cofinite topology. If formula_1 is finite then the cofinite topology is simply the discrete topology. If formula_1 is not finite then this topology is not Hausdorff (T2), regular or normal because no two nonempty open sets are disjoint (that is, it is hyperconnected).

===Double-pointed cofinite topology===

The double-pointed cofinite topology is the cofinite topology with every point doubled; that is, it is the topological product of the cofinite topology with the indiscrete topology on a two-element set. It is not T0 or T1, since the points of each doublet are topologically indistinguishable. It is, however, R0 since topologically distinguishable points are separated. The space is compact as the product of two compact spaces; alternatively, it is compact because each nonempty open set contains all but finitely many points.

For an example of the countable double-pointed cofinite topology, the set formula_26 of integers can be given a topology such that every even number formula_27 is topologically indistinguishable from the following odd number formula_28. The closed sets are the unions of finitely many pairs formula_29 or the whole set. The open sets are the complements of the closed sets; namely, each open set consists of all but a finite number of pairs formula_29 or is the empty set.

==Other examples==

===Product topology===
The product topology on a product of topological spaces formula_31 has basis formula_32 where formula_33 is open, and cofinitely many formula_34

The analog without requiring that cofinitely many factors are the whole space is the box topology.

===Direct sum===
The elements of the direct sum of modules formula_35 are sequences formula_36 where cofinitely many formula_37

The analog without requiring that cofinitely many summands are zero is the direct product.

